39:07.645 --> 39:12.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the scientific community, a
renaissance
in thinking about psychedelic
drugs like MDMA,

39:12.850 --> 39:18.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LSD and psilocybin, the drug
found in magic
mushrooms.

39:18.189 --> 39:21.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN ROSS, NYU Langone
Medical Center:
Psychiatrists are really
yearning to have

39:21.192 --> 39:26.264 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
something that works
differently, that works
quickly, that lasts longer to
add to their

39:26.297 --> 39:27.265 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
toolbox.

39:27.298 --> 39:29.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's really important to do
that.

39:29.133 --> 39:34.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Stephen Ross is a
psychiatrist
and addiction specialist at NYU
Langone Medical

39:34.539 --> 39:35.940 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Center.

39:35.974 --> 39:41.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He is exploring the medical uses
of psilocybin,
a close cousin of LSD.

39:41.045 --> 39:46.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says the drugs are safe, but
only in a
carefully controlled setting.

39:46.150 --> 39:47.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Can you overdose?

39:47.385 --> 39:49.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN ROSS: There are no known
overdoses
with psilocybin.

39:50.021 --> 39:52.957 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not known to have a toxic
dose.

39:52.991 --> 39:55.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's considered safe
physiologically.

39:55.059 --> 39:59.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, psychologically, that's
where the potential
damage and danger is.

39:59.264 --> 40:04.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's why these drugs, in
uncontrolled
settings, can create anxiety,
they can create

40:04.535 --> 40:06.838 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
paranoia, they can create
dangerous behavior.

40:06.871 --> 40:12.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Skeptics say the
studies are
relatively small, and it's
extremely difficult

40:12.310 --> 40:15.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to compare these drugs with a
placebo.

40:15.747 --> 40:20.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Concerns notwithstanding,
researchers across
the nation are tuning in and
turning on to

40:20.985 --> 40:28.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
psychedelics a few generations
after psychologist
Timothy Leary unintentionally
stigmatized

40:28.059 --> 40:29.794 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

40:29.827 --> 40:36.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the 1960s, Leary conducted a
series of
valid experiments with LSD and
psilocybin,

40:36.267 --> 40:42.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but as he devolved into an
infamous psychedelic
poster boy, the drugs escaped
the lab.

40:42.173 --> 40:46.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: The natural state of the
brain is chaos.

40:46.344 --> 40:51.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In 1970, the
federal government
made the drugs illegal, in the
same category

40:51.949 --> 40:53.751 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as heroin.

40:53.785 --> 40:58.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The mainstream medical community
tapped out,
even though there was a lot of
data suggesting

40:58.122 --> 41:01.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the drugs might help people with
certain mental
illnesses.

41:01.292 --> 41:07.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN ROSS: I was fascinated
that, how could
this have been such a big part
of a psychiatry

41:07.365 --> 41:10.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that I never heard about it,
completely
buried in my training?

41:10.134 --> 41:13.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that just made me really
curious to look
further into it.

41:13.204 --> 41:18.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Much remains a
mystery, but
advanced neuroimaging has
provided some new

41:18.443 --> 41:20.211 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
clues.

41:20.244 --> 41:25.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Psilocybin seems to quiet brain
areas known
as the default mode network,
essentially our

41:25.883 --> 41:27.518 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
autopilot mode.

41:27.552 --> 41:32.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this might help break the
chains of addiction,
or lift the fog of depression.

41:32.623 --> 41:36.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN ROSS: So it's plausible
that sort
of deactivating that network can
take someone

41:36.594 --> 41:39.664 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
away from a stuck pathologic
rhythm into something
else.

41:39.697 --> 41:45.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The Mithoefers
are working
on a similar hypothesis as they
study MDMA

41:45.570 --> 41:48.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and its effects on PTSD.

41:48.072 --> 41:51.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They too suspect the drug helps
break a cycle.

41:51.075 --> 41:52.877 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

41:52.910 --> 41:56.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MITHOEFER: We know that
people with
PTSD have increased activity in
the amygdala,

41:56.848 --> 42:00.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the fear center, and they have
decreased activity
in the prefrontal cortex.

42:00.852 --> 42:04.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The amygdala is
at the center
of our brain.

42:04.655 --> 42:10.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is what creates our emotional
reactions,
pleasant and unpleasant,
including sadness,

42:10.328 --> 42:12.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
anxiety and fear.

42:12.230 --> 42:17.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The prefrontal cortex, our
executive brain,
is where we temper those
emotions through

42:17.402 --> 42:19.203 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rational decision-making.

42:19.237 --> 42:27.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MDMA decreases activity in the
amygdala and
increases activity in the
prefrontal cortex.

42:27.678 --> 42:32.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it tamps down the negative
emotions in
the first place and also
increases the brain's

42:33.017 --> 42:36.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ability to keep those feelings
in check.

42:36.821 --> 42:42.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Researchers aren't sure whether
the drug works
by causing direct changes in
brain chemistry,

42:42.427 --> 42:45.930 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or simply by making trauma
easier to talk
about and process.

42:45.963 --> 42:47.832 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

42:47.865 --> 42:52.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MITHOEFER: What we see
in the sessions
is that it seems to kind of
bring people down

42:52.937 --> 43:01.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from being overwhelmed by
emotions, but also
kind of bring them up from being
numbed out

43:01.078 --> 43:03.414 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or disconnected from emotions.

43:03.448 --> 43:05.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's when the therapeutic
change happens.

43:05.983 --> 43:10.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: With both drugs,
doctors use
a similar approach.

43:10.855 --> 43:16.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Ross showed me the room
where he and his
team conduct therapy Sessions
for subjects

43:16.527 --> 43:18.329 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
under the influence of
psilocybin.

43:18.362 --> 43:24.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN ROSS: We walk over to
them, give them
the pill, some water, they take
it, and then

43:24.869 --> 43:29.040 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they will essentially sit here
for about half-an-hour.

43:29.073 --> 43:33.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We will turn the music on, the
pre-selected
music, give them some art books,
or they will

43:33.244 --> 43:35.146 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
meditate a little bit.

43:35.179 --> 43:38.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then after, about
half-an-hour, when they're
feeling something, we will
instruct them into

43:38.349 --> 43:39.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the default position.

43:39.617 --> 43:42.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lie down on your back, eye
shades, music.

43:42.587 --> 43:45.590 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the two therapists sit here
for many hours.

43:45.623 --> 43:50.895 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In December, Ross
and colleagues
published a paper on the impact
of psilocybin

43:50.928 --> 43:55.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for people with severe anxiety
or depression
due to a grave illness.

43:55.800 --> 44:01.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They found that a single dose of
psilocybin
reliably helped 60 percent to 80
percent of

44:01.339 --> 44:06.410 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them feel better immediately,
and for as long
as six months.

44:06.444 --> 44:08.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Researchers at Johns Hopkins
reported similar
results.

44:08.980 --> 44:14.385 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
ESTALYN WALCOFF,
Psychotherapist: My name
is Estalyn Walcoff and I work as
a psychotherapist.

44:14.418 --> 44:17.688 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Estalyn Walcoff
was a subject
in the NYU study.

44:17.722 --> 44:23.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ESTALYN WALCOFF: It was as if
this spirit
that I had hoped to connect to
was so much

44:23.828 --> 44:28.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bigger and stronger than I had
ever imagined.

44:28.599 --> 44:30.201 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I was quaking in my boots.

44:30.234 --> 44:34.405 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Ross and
Mithoefer say it's
important to temper the
enthusiasm.

44:34.438 --> 44:36.073 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

44:36.107 --> 44:42.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MITHOEFER: This seems to
be a very
powerful tool, but it is only a
tool.

44:42.313 --> 44:48.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's the person's own
healing process
and their relationships, the
therapeutic relationships,

44:48.252 --> 44:50.988 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that support that that are very
important.

44:51.022 --> 44:54.292 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there is the danger of
people thinking
of it as a magic bullet.

44:54.325 --> 44:55.993 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN ROSS: We're following
the data.

44:56.027 --> 44:59.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't think that this is
going to cure
anything or change the world.

44:59.764 --> 45:04.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are focused on helping sick
people and
just doing more science and
following the

45:04.335 --> 45:05.636 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
data, seeing where it leads.

45:05.670 --> 45:09.874 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Both drugs may
soon be put
to a bigger test.

45:09.907 --> 45:15.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Researchers are asking the
government to approve
some major trials, with hundreds
of subjects,

45:15.646 --> 45:17.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
some time this year.

45:17.648 --> 45:26.958 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Miles O'Brien, the "PBS
NewsHour," New York.

45:26.991 --> 45:34.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight:
remembering
a TV legend, Mary Tyler Moore.

45:34.832 --> 45:39.470 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And back to Jeffrey Brown, who
has our remembrance.

45:39.503 --> 45:49.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: It was sitcom
television that
signaled and helped push larger
cultural change,

45:49.614 --> 45:55.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"The Mary Tyler Moore Show" in
the 1970s,
in which the actress played a
single, 30-something

45:55.686 --> 46:01.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
working woman, Mary Richards, a
TV producer
at a local Minneapolis station,
here with

46:01.726 --> 46:04.228 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
her boss, played by Ed Asner.

46:04.261 --> 46:06.664 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ED ASNER, Actor: You know what?

46:06.697 --> 46:08.265 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You have got spunk.

46:08.299 --> 46:09.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:09.300 --> 46:10.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARY TYLER MOORE, Actress:
Well...

46:10.701 --> 46:12.670 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ED ASNER: I hate spunk.

46:12.703 --> 46:13.671 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:13.704 --> 46:15.473 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ED ASNER: I'll tell you what.

46:15.506 --> 46:18.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I will try you out for a couple
of weeks and
see how it works out.

46:18.809 --> 46:22.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If I don't like you, I will fire
you.

46:22.113 --> 46:23.681 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARY TYLER MOORE: Right, right.

46:23.714 --> 46:26.317 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ED ASNER: If you don't like me,
I will fire
you.

46:26.350 --> 46:27.318 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:27.351 --> 46:28.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARY TYLER MOORE: That certainly
seems fair.

46:28.352 --> 46:30.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I will get a towel from the
kitchen.

46:30.121 --> 46:31.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the '60s,
Moore had been
a beloved figure in a more
traditional role

46:31.922 --> 46:36.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for women, as the frazzled, but
often hilarious
wife of Dick Van Dyke on the
show bearing

46:36.894 --> 46:37.928 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his name.

46:37.962 --> 46:41.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARY TYLER MOORE: Snow White
lived.

46:41.799 --> 46:42.767 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:42.800 --> 46:47.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DICK VAN DYKE, Actor: Oh, what a
day.

46:47.538 --> 46:49.306 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:49.340 --> 46:55.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Over the years,
she won seven
Emmy Awards for her television
roles, and

46:55.613 --> 47:01.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an Oscar-nominated performance
in the 1980
film "Ordinary People," the
story of a disintegrating

47:01.952 --> 47:05.556 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
family following a son's death.

47:05.589 --> 47:10.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Moore wrote and spoke of her own
struggles,
a battle with alcoholism, and
with the diabetes

47:10.861 --> 47:13.764 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
she lived with for some 40
years.

47:13.798 --> 47:16.667 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She was also a champion for
animal rights.

47:16.701 --> 47:21.172 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mary Tyler Moore was 80 years
old.

47:21.205 --> 47:25.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A short time ago, I spoke with
Dick Cavett.

47:25.676 --> 47:29.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He interviewed Mary Tyler Moore
a number of
times over the years, and was a
good friend.

47:29.547 --> 47:34.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I began by asking about her
talent as a comic
actor.

47:34.452 --> 47:39.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Dick Cavett, thanks so much for
joining us.

47:39.190 --> 47:43.461 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First, Mary Tyler Moore, the
comic performer,
what did she have?

47:43.494 --> 47:47.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DICK CAVETT, Entertainer: She
had it all.

47:47.131 --> 47:48.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She had everything.

47:48.666 --> 47:52.770 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And she had more than many comic
performers.

47:52.803 --> 48:01.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We had that period of so many
wonderful what
used to be called comediennes,
Lucy and Carol

48:01.579 --> 48:02.580 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Mary.

48:02.613 --> 48:04.715 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Mary was extremely beautiful.

48:04.749 --> 48:06.250 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that doesn't necessarily go
up to that
period of time with comediennes.

48:06.283 --> 48:08.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were either scrawny or had
bad hair or
looked funny.

48:08.052 --> 48:13.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to be a beauty and to be a
comedienne,
witty, and even, when required,
slapstick,

48:13.858 --> 48:15.993 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Mary had it all.

48:16.026 --> 48:25.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once, a writer on the show said,
Mary is the
only person I have ever worked
with who made

48:25.970 --> 48:26.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
every script better.

48:26.971 --> 48:28.739 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I said, be specific.

48:28.773 --> 48:33.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he said, all can I say is,
when we gave
Mary the script, we found laughs
in straight

48:33.210 --> 48:37.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
lines that we didn't know were
there.

48:37.515 --> 48:42.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mary had the greatest laugh, the
gutsiest,
almost really bawdy laugh that
you rarely

48:42.520 --> 48:44.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
saw her do on television, a
great sense of
humor.

48:44.789 --> 48:54.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Though we didn't have the term
glass ceilings,
she in fact came through one,
and made it

48:54.732 --> 48:59.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
better for a lot of other women
in television
by showing that she was somebody
who was -- a

48:59.503 --> 49:05.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
woman could pull, pull the
audience in a very
big way.

49:05.509 --> 49:09.814 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, Dick
Cavett, thank
you very much for joining us.

49:09.847 --> 49:14.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for some more perspective on
Mary Tyler
Moore's influence, I'm joined
now by Cynthia

49:14.051 --> 49:15.586 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Littleton of "Variety."

49:15.619 --> 49:18.556 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She has written about Moore and
is the author
of two books about television.

49:18.589 --> 49:23.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, Cynthia, it's almost
hard to think
back to TV in those days, the
kinds of subjects

49:23.194 --> 49:26.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that were not discussed, the way
women were
